Oil dest ined for the U.S. Gulf Coast was typically taken by tanker from Valdez, Alaska, to the Pacific side of Panama and then transported by pipeline to the Atlantic side of Panama, where it was reloaded onto tankers for the trip to its final destination, such as Louisiana.
Shipments to the Mid-C ontinent went from Valdez to Los Angeles and from there by pipeline to their final des tinations.
